	h4.cd Summary
	p.cd Quick and efficient disease diagnostics require percision, innovation, and ingenuity. Current diagnostic tests are often performed by lab technicians and can take 24 to 48 hours to heed results. Accurate and reliable results can influence treatment plans to avoid unnecessary follow up appointments. As an undergraduate researcher in the MML, I am developing technology that simplifies the diagnostic process. The final product is a tool that can be integrated into a sample preparation device to be used by a variety of audiences including primary care physicians and doctors in developing countries.

	h4.cd The Technology
	p.cd Rather than waiting for an analyte sample to interact with an activated surface, our solution involves an efficient matrix of activated low melting point (LMP) agarose beads. The large surface area results in little to no delays in diffusion time, allowing for rapid binding reactions and the identification of small concentrations of analyte. Quantifying the amount of analyte requires a specific technique to overcome the opaque nature of the capture matrix. LMP agarose beads can be melted by an external heater to create a solid and transparent mass, overcoming light scatter and limited optical detection caused by silicon beads, monoliths, and agarose.

	h4.cd Challenges
	ul
		li Assess the validity of our assumption that melting agarose beads is feasible and has an optical improvement
		li Determine an effective chemical reaction to activate the agarose surface and detect the target analyte
		li Create ~30 µm diameter LMP agarose beads in large quantities, eliminate clogging, and maintain high consistency in size distribution to avoid bead coalescing
		li Verify the assay in a sample end device

	h4.cd Progress
	p.cd This is an ongoing project that I have the opportunity of working on throughout the remainder of the academic year thanks to the University of Maryland SEEDS fellowship program and the Maryland Technology ASPIRE grant.

