	p.cd Producing agarose beads has proven to be the most difficult component. Agarose is a finicky material because at room temperature it quickly gels and a gelling solution inside a microfluidic chip can alter internal pressures and flow rates or simply clog the device. However when I want the beads to gel into distinct beads, I need the beads to quickly cool.
	p.cd Finding a solution that met both needs is tricky, but I have made signifiant progress. Currently, I have built a platform nicknamed “Turtle-Bot” for its acrylic legs. The microfluidic chip is placed on top of peltier tiles, one around 40°C and the second around 5-10°C. Each tile is controlled by a raspberry pi with a PI controller. The combination of the 3D printed parts and laser cut supports allowed for rapid prototyping of this approach with a very fast turnaround.

